Realistically, Joseph's comparison (and I'm not picking on Joseph here;
Dave and lots of other OS/2 advocates also make this comparison) isn't
all that accurate.

Many people equate OS/2 now with Windows 3.0 four years ago when talking
about application availability.  When OS/2 2.0 came out, that was compared 
to Windows 3.0.  ("Of course there aren't any apps.  They take time to 
develop.  How many apps did Windows 3.0 have when it first came out?")
When OS/2 2.1 came out, *that* was compared with Windows 3.0.  Now it's
Warp's turn.  Will Warp's release spur OS/2 app development?  Sure, it
probably will to some degree, but the situation with Warp now and
Windows 3.0 in 1990 is still quite different.

Here's a simple exercise you can carry out:  Find the areas where the 
situation with OS/2 now is the same as the situation with Windows in 
1990.  Then look at the areas where the situations are different.

-----
Windows in 1990:

The dominant platform at the time is DOS.  DOS apps work, and work well,
but you can only run one at a time, they're usually character based, and
they're a pain to develop (640K, everthing needs device drivers, screen
drivers, printer drivers, etc...).  OS/2 1.x is also on the scene, but
it requres a lot of resources, has poor DOS compatibility, few and 
expensive apps, and a really bad reputation.  It's stable, but has only
sold about 500K copies.

Windows 3.0 is released and, for whatever reason, starts to sell big.  It's
graphical and multi-tasking.  It's easier to use, has a consistent interface,
and it's very different from DOS.

The major competitor at the time is, as I said, DOS.  Made by Microsoft.
Just like Windows 3.0.  DOS is in widespread use, and still growing, but
it doesn't look like it's going to be improved much anymore (and, for the
most part, hasn't been).  After all, OS/2 was supposed to be "the next DOS", 
but it looks like it flopped.  If you didn't like DOS, all you had was
Windows.

So, Microsoft decides their strategic direction is Windows.  Some companies 
start developing Windows applications (which aren't limited to 640K, don't
need their own drivers, are easier to use, look better, etc...).  At first,
they aren't very good, but sales start to pick up.  Windows starts getting
bundled with a lot of systems (as well as all sorts of other things).
Windows app sales are growing faster than the DOS market (which is still
growing, but slowly).

Soon, ISVs have a choice: Stick with what they know (DOS), or develop for
the future (Windows).  Many of them (Lotus, Borland, WordPerfect)
eventually choose the future, which, by default, means Windows.


Within two or so years of release, Windows apps pull in more revenue than
DOS apps.  Windows apps are very good -- the best PC apps you can get in some
categories.  The Windows market is clearly exploding, while the DOS market
is stagnant.  If you want Windows bundled, almost anybody will sell it
to you.  (Some give it to you whether you want it or not.)  Until OS/2 2.0
comes out in March 1992, Windows has the market to itself.  No competitors
to speak of.  It's firmly entrenched, everything (except dBase :) ) is
available for Windows, and sales of the OS reach eight digits.


-----
OS/2 today:

The dominant platform is Windows 3.1.  Windows 3.1 apps work and work well.
For most mainstream categories, Windows apps are the best you can get on
a PC.  However, Windows is single-threaded, has little memory protection, is
16-bit, etc...  Windows apps are a pain to develop (64K segments, cooperative
multitasking, etc...), but there are thousands (tens of thousands?) of
skilled Windows programmers out there.  DOS is still around, but sales of
DOS apps have declined drastically (a fraction of Windows app sales, by 
revenue), and dropping, while Windows app sales are exploding.

OS/2 3.0 is about to be released.  It has a lot of great features.  However,
for the most part, it's only an incremental improvement over OS/2 2.1.
It's better than Windows, but isn't as different as Windows was from DOS.
It's more stable.  It has preemptive multitasking.  It's multithreaded.
It has the Workplace Shell.

But there's one huge difference in the situations:  In 1990, Windows was
going up against DOS, and DOS wasn't going anywhere.  Today, OS/2 is going
up against Windows.  Windows is made by a competing company that bet their
future on it, and Windows isn't sitting still.

-----

ISVs today have a choice: Stick with what they know, or develop for the
future.  Up to here, you could argue that there's still some sort of
parallel between the two situations.  Suppose, however, that they use
history as a guide and choose to develop for the future.  Now they have
another choice that they didn't have back in 1990:  Which future?  

And that's where the parallel falls apart.

     - Mike


