Yes -- and it gets worse for Microsoft. Consider: as of April 30, '95. 
Microsoft declares Windows 3.1 dead. Formerly, there was no other option;
it was DOS (the past) or Win3.0 (the future). 

Joseph points out that many say, "Why develop for OS/2 when it runs 
Win3.1? I'll write Win3.1 apps, and cover both markets." And the
same argument was used before with Win3.1 & DOS, much to the detriment
of those who made the argument. 

Let's not kid ourselves: the road to Cairo goes through Chicago (and 
those very words were used by Paul Maritz at the Windows World keynote
address July in Chicago). Chicago is a temporary stop, a way station
en route to an object oriented NT. I for one will be astonished if
Chicago can do anything more than boot with only 8MB. 

So the argument falls apart according to Mike because there is a choice.
But I say it's worse this time for Redmond, because last time, *both
choices were owned by Microsoft*. It ain't that way this time, is it?

There have been horror stories galore about Warp II in c.o.o.misc and
c.o.o.beta; but if IBM can get its act together and release a good,
fast version in October, they'll have almost half a year till Chicago's
version 1.0 release. Not to spread uncertainty, but Microsoft's track
record with version 1.0 of Windows releases has not been spectacularly
successful.

Very soon now, ISV's are gonna have to make a choice: Win95, or OS/2, or
Win3.1. We know what the past is. I submit that the future is up for
grabs, and IBM gets a few shots at the brass ring before Microsoft even
comes around once.

David Derbes [derbes@uhuru.uchicago.edu]

