I agree.  This was the real problem with the Win32s addition to OS/2: if
OS/2 and Windows were going to split at Chicago, Win32s should never have been
added to Os/2.

But IBM knows that, if they go their own way, Chicago is going to go through
OS/2 like a Garden Weasel through a Kleenex, which is why they added Win32s and
why this whole issue is moot.

However --

>The funny thing is, MS won't be competing in the Win32s market (i.e. OS/2),

They most certainly will be.  The "Win32s" market doesn't exist.  The only
Win32 platform restricted to Win32s is Windows 3.1 -- and on Windows 3.1
(which includes WIN-OS/2 and Windows-under-OS/2) the penalties of Win32s
(increased memory usage, thunking overhead) are only worthwhile if your app
gains significantly from being a 32bit program.  Word, Excel, PowerPoint, 
Access (debatable) and so on don't benefit from this.

And there are Win16 versions of all of them.  For Win32 users, MS will offer
the first two Office apps this Fall/Winter.  

If having both 32bit lfn-aware, multiuser-aware Win32 version and 16bit
versions is not "competing" -- well, that's an interesting definition.

>such that all other developers have a huge carrot for eschewing Win32c and
>sticking with the lowest common denominator (Win32s). 

Then again, the carrot encouraging Win32"c" development will probably arrive
around the same time as Windows '95, don't you think?  I think the release
of, or the *threat* of the release of a fully "Chicago-ized" suite of Office/32
products will get companies like WP, Lotus and Borland off their butts and into
the development meetings because MS has whacked them before with the same 
strategy.  See: Excel.

>MS has shot itself
>in the foot, especially if they aren't aggressive about delivering their
>own applications as multithreaded Win32c's.

I agree, but from MS's point of view, this can wait.  I don't believe for
one second that the post-Chicago versions of Word, Excel, etc. wont be 
mulththreaded, sport new interface gadgets, and be Win32/Win32c-specific. 
It would be too big of an upgrade market (and Chicago booster) to let get
by.  They may be (to my disappointment) biding their time and not particularly
bothering with NT development, but they will.

You can always trust MS to make money.  If Lotus, WP and others don't match
their development direction, MS will only make more.


