You got the cart in front of the horse.  
Who cares what a programmer is tempted to do?  

"Let's build a win32 app becuase we know WIN16" logic has NOT worked
very well yet.  In fact it does not work at all.  I recall that UNIX
vendors are doing NT apps so win16 is not the driving force.  Is it in
your case?

With NT at *only* 200-300 a copy we'll not see many WIN32 NT3.5 users
driving WIN32 app sales through the roof.
Its all up to WIN95. 

