So far it *has* been enough for OS/2 to add a few million users in
1993-94.  For some reason people just have not spent the $600 (16MB) to
run NT 3.1.  There are a lot of 8-16MB computers.

I'm a bit confuzsed on your UI comments.  What is WIN95 all about?  The
MAC?  IMHO the UI.  NT's old UI is a BIG liability. Not only is it old
but it will be changing soon which may discourage NT adoption now and
encourage waiting for WIN95.

Also, Historically OS's priced just a few hundred dollars more have
lost to cheaper OS's. (I'll debate that point with you).  CP/M vs.  DOS
and OS/2 1.x vs WIN3.0.  Now NT vs. OS/2. (yes NT is comparable to OS/2
and has been in product reviews and at one time NT was the reason OS/2
was doomed).

OS/2 is $15 - $79 compared to 200-300 for NT - If you can find it or
win32 apps.  I have not seen NT at the EggHeads' COMPUSA or FRY's in
Santa Clara County for months.  Tons of OS/2 and OS/2 for Windows (as
many as DOS and WIN3.1 IF NOT MORE) boxes on the shelves and even an
OS/2 section with sold out software.

MS needs to drop NT's price to $100 and - like you suggest - make a
stripped down version of NT for 8MB computers.
