: Not a bad analysis, but consider that Microsoft is offering yet
: another choice -- stick with what you know *and* develop for the
: future.  Win32 is basically a superset of Win16, but eliminates many
: of the headaches and provides everything OS/2 does and more.  That's
: gotta be tempting to Win16 programmers.

: I don't know for a fact that Win32 will displace Win16 over OS/2 3.0,
: but it's got a hell of a lot going for it -- and all OS/2 3.0 has
: going for it is a better user-interface (which hasn't meant squat
: historically) and slightly lower resource requirements (a few hundred
: dollars' difference at today's prices).  Will that be enough?

Win32 is an API, not an OS. Win32 is competing with the 32-bit PM API, 
which people who know both say is cleaner, simpler and makes more sense
than Win32. The bigger competition, however is OLE2 v. Opendoc, COM v. SOM.
IBM has the technological advantage here, but what will they _do_ with it?

Getting to the OS's, however, it comes down to Win95 v. OS/2 3.0. IBM is
rumored to have the biggest marketing push in the history of the PC
industry ready when Warp ships. Win95 has been getting a lot of bad press
recently, as people are slowly realizing its not all it was cracked up to
be. Who will win? Who will have the better marketing and the least bad
press? Who will have the more lucrative bundling deals? We'll have to wait
and see.

Side note: Does there even have to _be_ a winner? With 100million+ DOS
users looking to upgrade, is there enough room in the market for _both_
systems?
